Result Comment: THE ESTIMATED GFR MAY BE MISLEADING IN THE FOLLOWING SITUATIONS: EXTREMES OF AGE AND BODY SIZE, SEVERE MALNUTRITION OR OBESITY, DISEASES OF SKELETAL MUSCLE, PARAPLEGIA OR QUADREPLEGIA, VEGETARIAN DIET, MISSING LIMBS, AND RAPIDLY CHANGING KIDNEY FUNCTION (I.E. ACUTE RENAL FAILURE). CLINICAL STAGES 1 AND 2 CANNOT BE DETERMINED SOLELY BY CALCULATED GFR. SEE BELOW.
STAGES OF CHRONIC KIDNEY DISEASE
STAGE DESCRIPTION GFR(mL/min/1.73M2)
1 KIDNEY DAMAGE WITH >60
NORMAL OR INCREASED GFR
2 KIDNEY DAMAGE WITH >60

3 MODERATELY DECREASED GFR 30-59
4 SEVERELY DECREASED GFR 15-29
5 KIDNEY FAILURE <15

Result Comment: *** PLEASE NOTE NEW METHODOLOGY IN USE. ***
ASSAY MANUFACTURER IS BECKMAN COULTER. METHODOLOGY IS IMMUNOENZYMATIC ASSAY.
RESULTS OBTAINED WITH DIFFERENT ASSAY METHODS CANNOT BE USED INTERCHANGEABLY.
TNIHS VALUES ABOVE 4.9 NG/L MAY BE CLINICALLY SIGNIFICANT. RECOMMEND REPEAT TESTING WITH A NEW SAMPLE AT 2 HOURS.
AN INCREASING DELTA CHANGE OF 16 NG/L OR MORE, OR A TNIHS REPORTED VALUE EQUAL TO OR GREATER THAN 50 NG/L IS CONSIDERED POSITIVE.
ALL PATIENTS WITH AN ELEVATED BLOOD TROPONIN LEVEL HAVE MYOCARDIAL INJURY. CLINICALLY, THE MOST IMPORTANT USE OF TROPONIN TESTING IS TO IDENTIFY PATIENTS SUSPECTED OF HAVING AN ACUTE CORONARY SYNDROME (ACS).
ELEVATED CARDIAC TROPONIN LEVELS ARE NOT SPECIFIC FOR THE DIAGNOSIS OF ACS OR ACUTE SPONTANEOUS MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION (TYPE 1 MI).
MYOCARDIAL STRAIN FROM NON-ACS CONDITIONS (TYPE 2 MI) SUCH AS SEPSIS, CONGESTIVE HEART FAILURE, MYOCARDITIS, DRUG TOXICITY, PULMONARY EMBOLISM, HYPOXIA, AND TRAUMA CAN BE ASSOCIATED WITH ELEVATED TROPONIN LEVELS.
EXTENDED EVALUATION MAY BE NECESSARY TO MAKE AN ACCURATE DIAGNOSIS.
